@etem In general `send_command` works more reliably and generally should be used in cases when the router's prompt is returned. `send_command` also has an argument for a regular expression pattern to detect (instead of the trailing prompt).

`send_command_timing` is entirely timing based and tries to figure out when the command is done based on no more data being available. I use it in cases like the above or in situations where the router prompts for more information in a command.

Pretty much all delays in Netmiko are affected by `global_delay_factor` so yes send_command_timing's delays would be modified by this.

