The reason the `pickle` overloading happens by default is: (1) historical, this is the design choice I made before I had a `revert` capacity, and (2) functional, to use `dill` in a parallel library, you have to replace `pickle` with `dill`… this is not often possible, but bootstrapping in the `dill` registry to `pickle` can enable libraries you don't want to fork to now work, and (3) it's "easier" than importing `dill` then having to remember to "bootstrap" `pickle`.

So, again, why overload `pickle` by default?  Eh… mostly for historical reasons. 

@matsjoyce is also correct, Trying to pickle a `lambda` with `pickle` after an `import dill` will yield a `_pickle.PicklingError`… and `_pickle` is the C version of `pickle`.  `dill` only overloads the python version of `pickle`.

